description: From New Latin energeticus (16th c.), or its source, Ancient Greek ἐνεργητικός (energētikós), from ἐνεργέω (energéō, “to be active”), from ἐνεργός (energós, “active”). By surface analysis, from energy +‎ -etic.

adjectives.description: energetic (comparative more energetic, superlative most energetic)

entries.meaning: (sciences) Possessing or pertaining to energy. [from 19th c.]
examples: Cosmic rays are energetic particles from outer space.

entries.meaning: Characterised by force or vigour; full of energy; lively, vigorous. [from 18th c.]
examples: Those kids are so energetic: they want to run around playing all day.

entries.meaning: (obsolete) Having powerful effects; efficacious, potent. [17th–20th c.]

description: Possibly from a clipping of energetic materials.

entries.meaning: (materials science, chiefly in the plural) Any material utilized for its release of energy, either as an explosive, propellant, or for pyrotechnic effects.
